Driver performance monitoring affects route assignments and service timing. Drivers with better safety records and customer satisfaction scores receive priority assignments for challenging routes or high-value passengers. This creates service quality variations that benefit some passengers while potentially extending wait times for others.

The quality control system includes passenger feedback processing that influences future service delivery. Negative feedback about specific drivers, vehicles, or route timing affects operational assignments, but feedback implementation often takes weeks to reflect in actual service changes.

Equipment maintenance scheduling creates planned service disruptions that affect route availability but aren't always communicated clearly to passengers. Vehicles require regular maintenance that removes them from service during predetermined windows, affecting capacity and potentially extending wait times.

